# UTF-8 And Mojibake Safety

This rule comes from the 2026-06-18 `frontend/src/App.vue` encoding incident.

## Mandatory Rules

1. Keep source and documentation in UTF-8. Prefer UTF-8 without BOM for new text files.
2. Do not use `Set-Content`, `Out-File`, shell redirection, `echo`, or heredocs to rewrite an existing Unicode source file.
3. Use `apply_patch` or an encoding-aware editor for scoped changes.
4. If bulk rewriting is unavoidable, write an explicitly UTF-8 temporary candidate, validate it, review its diff, then replace the formal file.
5. Create a backup or confirm a recoverable Git commit before any risky transformation.
6. Treat U+FFFD and literal `?` as potentially irreversible loss.
7. Split patches at the incident boundary before using them as recovery sources.
8. Never trust terminal appearance alone; use strict byte decoding and Git diff.
9. Never stop verification at `npm run build` when Vue first-render state or functional text changed.

## Required Checks

```powershell
node .cursor/skills/encoding-mojibake-guard/scripts/check-text-integrity.mjs <changed-files>
```

For `frontend/src/App.vue` also run:

```powershell
node .cursor/skills/encoding-mojibake-guard/scripts/check-vue-form-contract.mjs frontend/src/App.vue
node tmp/check_vue_candidate.js frontend/src/App.vue
npm --prefix frontend run build
```

If the change can affect first render or interaction, verify it in a real browser and require zero console errors.

